{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529720"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.1,0.59,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7141"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55450"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7141"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"255"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2228"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4605"},{"type":"tags","id":"4606"},{"type":"tags","id":"4612"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"5605"},{"type":"tags","id":"5623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17047"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit with severe community-acquired pneumonia and septic shock. She has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her regular medications include metformin, amlodipine and a budesonide/formoterol inhaler. On examination, she appears critically unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 88% on 15 L/min oxygen via non-rebreather mask, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. She is confused and has greatly increased work of breathing. Arterial blood gas shows pH 7.28, PaCO2 50 mmHg, PaO2 58 mmHg, HCO3 22 mmol/L, and lactate 4.5 mmol/L. The decision is made to intubate the patient.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate induction agent for this patient\u0027s intubation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fentanyl","Thiopental","Midazolam","Ketamine","Propofol"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the patient is critically ill with septic shock and respiratory failure requiring emergency intubation. The choice of induction agent is crucial, as it can significantly impact the patient\u0027s hemodynamic stability during the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKetamine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate induction agent for this patient. It is preferred in septic shock due to its unique pharmacological properties. Ketamine maintains or even increases blood pressure and cardiac output through sympathetic stimulation, which is beneficial in hypotensive patients. Additionally, it has bronchodilating properties, which can be helpful in patients with respiratory distress. These characteristics make ketamine an ideal choice for induction in critically ill patients with hemodynamic instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropofol\u003C/strong\u003E, while commonly used for induction, can cause significant hypotension, especially in patients who are already hemodynamically unstable. This effect is due to its vasodilatory properties and myocardial depression. In a septic patient with pre-existing hypotension, propofol could precipitate cardiovascular collapse and is therefore not the best choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E, while an excellent analgesic, is not typically used as a sole induction agent for intubation. In septic patients, it should be used cautiously due to its potential to cause hypotension, especially in larger doses. While it might be used in small doses as part of a balanced induction technique, it\u0027s not the most appropriate primary induction agent in this hemodynamically unstable patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidazolam\u003C/strong\u003E, a benzodiazepine, can cause hypotension and respiratory depression. While it\u0027s sometimes used for sedation in critically ill patients, it\u0027s not typically a first-line agent for rapid sequence induction in emergency intubations, especially in hemodynamically unstable patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiopental\u003C/strong\u003E, a barbiturate, is rarely used in modern practice for induction of anesthesia, especially in critically ill patients. It can cause significant hypotension and myocardial depression, making it unsuitable for patients in septic shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to choosing ketamine as the induction agent, the intubation should be performed using a rapid sequence induction (RSI) technique to minimize the risk of aspiration. This would typically involve pre-oxygenation, administration of ketamine followed immediately by a neuromuscular blocking agent (such as rocuronium or succinylcholine/suxamethonium), and then proceeding directly to laryngoscopy and intubation without bag-mask ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ketamine is the preferred induction agent for intubation in septic shock due to its cardiovascular stability and bronchodilating properties.","Rapid sequence induction is the preferred method for emergency intubation in critically ill patients to minimize aspiration risk."],"references":["Higgs, A. et al. Guidelines for the management of tracheal intubation in critically ill adults. British Journal of Anaesthesia, Volume 120, Issue 2, 323 - 352. Available from: https://www.bjanaesthesia.org/article/S0007-0912(17)54060-X/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-15T16:06:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T16:08:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7141"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55450"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":